    "last_edit_date" : 1618476529,
    "creation_date" : 1438371099,
    "answer_id" : 31753839,
    "question_id" : 31731014,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>You are using the <code>@aar</code> notation.<br />\nIt means that you want to download only the <code>aar</code> artifact, and no transitive dependencies.</p>\n<p>You can check Dependency management in Gradle\nin the official  <a href=\"https://docs.gradle.org/current/userguide/dependency_management.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">documentation</a>. In particular:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>An artifact only notation creates a module dependency which downloads only the artifact file with the specified extension. <strong>Existing module descriptors are ignored</strong>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Using the <code>@aar</code> notation if you want to download the dependencies, you should <strong>add</strong> <code>transitive=true</code>.</p>\n<p>I'd expect that omitting @aar it should work without adding the transitive attribute.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 8991816,
      "reputation" : 21,
      "user_id" : 6703435,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08a924d7e9c068f686f2c829342db888?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "user6703435",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6703435/user6703435"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1470896418,
    "creation_date" : 1470896418,
    "answer_id" : 38888648,
    "question_id" : 31731014,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Sets whether this dependency should be resolved including or excluding its transitive dependencies. The artifacts belonging to this dependency might themselve have dependencies on other artifacts. The latter are called transitive dependencies.</p>\n"
  }, {
